00090 /*
00091 c     --------------------------------------------------------------
00092 c             DESCRIPTION OF THE VARIABLES IN L-BFGS-B
00093 c     --------------------------------------------------------------
00094 c
00095 c     n is an INTEGER variable that must be set by the user to the
00096 c       number of variables.  It is not altered by the routine.
00097 c
00098 c     m is an INTEGER variable that must be set by the user to the
00099 c       number of corrections used in the limited memory matrix.
00100 c       It is not altered by the routine.  Values of m < 3  are
00101 c       not recommended, and large values of m can result in excessive
00102 c       computing time. The range  3 <= m <= 20 is recommended. 
00103 c
00104 c     x is a DOUBLE PRECISION array of length n.  On initial entry
00105 c       it must be set by the user to the values of the initial
00106 c       estimate of the solution vector.  Upon successful exit, it
00107 c       contains the values of the variables at the best point
00108 c       found (usually an approximate solution).
00109 c
00110 c     l is a DOUBLE PRECISION array of length n that must be set by
00111 c       the user to the values of the lower bounds on the variables. If
00112 c       the i-th variable has no lower bound, l(i) need not be defined.
00113 c
00114 c     u is a DOUBLE PRECISION array of length n that must be set by
00115 c       the user to the values of the upper bounds on the variables. If
00116 c       the i-th variable has no upper bound, u(i) need not be defined.
00117 c
00118 c     nbd is an INTEGER array of dimension n that must be set by the
00119 c       user to the type of bounds imposed on the variables:
00120 c       nbd(i)=0 if x(i) is unbounded,
00121 c              1 if x(i) has only a lower bound,
00122 c              2 if x(i) has both lower and upper bounds, 
00123 c              3 if x(i) has only an upper bound.
00124 c
00125 c     f is a DOUBLE PRECISION variable.  If the routine setulb returns
00126 c       with task(1:2)= 'FG', then f must be set by the user to
00127 c       contain the value of the function at the point x.
00128 c
00129 c     g is a DOUBLE PRECISION array of length n.  If the routine setulb
00130 c       returns with taskb(1:2)= 'FG', then g must be set by the user to
00131 c       contain the components of the gradient at the point x.
00132 c
00133 c     factr is a DOUBLE PRECISION variable that must be set by the user.
00134 c       It is a tolerance in the termination test for the algorithm.
00135 c       The iteration will stop when
00136 c
00137 c        (f^k - f^{k+1})/max{|f^k|,|f^{k+1}|,1} <= factr*epsmch
00138 c
00139 c       where epsmch is the machine precision which is automatically
00140 c       generated by the code. Typical values for factr on a computer
00141 c       with 15 digits of accuracy in double precision are:
00142 c       factr=1.d+12 for low accuracy;
00143 c             1.d+7  for moderate accuracy; 
00144 c             1.d+1  for extremely high accuracy.
00145 c       The user can suppress this termination test by setting factr=0.
00146 c
00147 c     pgtol is a double precision variable.
00148 c       On entry pgtol >= 0 is specified by the user.  The iteration
00149 c         will stop when
00150 c
00151 c                 max{|proj g_i | i = 1, ..., n} <= pgtol
00152 c
00153 c         where pg_i is the ith component of the projected gradient.
00154 c       The user can suppress this termination test by setting pgtol=0.
00155 c
00156 c     wa is a DOUBLE PRECISION  array of length 
00157 c       (2mmax + 4)nmax + 12mmax^2 + 12mmax used as workspace.
00158 c       This array must not be altered by the user.
00159 c
00160 c     iwa is an INTEGER  array of length 3nmax used as
00161 c       workspace. This array must not be altered by the user.
00162 c
00163 c     task is a CHARACTER string of length 60.
00164 c       On first entry, it must be set to 'START'.
00165 c       On a return with task(1:2)='FG', the user must evaluate the
00166 c         function f and gradient g at the returned value of x.
00167 c       On a return with task(1:5)='NEW_X', an iteration of the
00168 c         algorithm has concluded, and f and g contain f(x) and g(x)
00169 c         respectively.  The user can decide whether to continue or stop
00170 c         the iteration. 
00171 c       When
00172 c         task(1:4)='CONV', the termination test in L-BFGS-B has been 
00173 c           satisfied;
00174 c         task(1:4)='ABNO', the routine has terminated abnormally
00175 c           without being able to satisfy the termination conditions,
00176 c           x contains the best approximation found,
00177 c           f and g contain f(x) and g(x) respectively;
00178 c         task(1:5)='ERROR', the routine has detected an error in the
00179 c           input parameters;
00180 c       On exit with task = 'CONV', 'ABNO' or 'ERROR', the variable task
00181 c         contains additional information that the user can print.
00182 c       This array should not be altered unless the user wants to
00183 c          stop the run for some reason.  See driver2 or driver3
00184 c          for a detailed explanation on how to stop the run 
00185 c          by assigning task(1:4)='STOP' in the driver.
00186 c
00187 c     iprint is an INTEGER variable that must be set by the user.
00188 c       It controls the frequency and type of output generated:
00189 c        iprint<0    no output is generated;
00190 c        iprint=0    print only one line at the last iteration;
00191 c        0<iprint<99 print also f and |proj g| every iprint iterations;
00192 c        iprint=99   print details of every iteration except n-vectors;
00193 c        iprint=100  print also the changes of active set and final x;
00194 c        iprint>100  print details of every iteration including x and g;
00195 c       When iprint > 0, the file iterate.dat will be created to
00196 c                        summarize the iteration.
00197 c
00198 c     csave  is a CHARACTER working array of length 60.
00199 c
00200 c     lsave is a LOGICAL working array of dimension 4.
00201 c       On exit with task = 'NEW_X', the following information is
00202 c         available:
00203 c       lsave(1) = .true.  the initial x did not satisfy the bounds;
00204 c       lsave(2) = .true.  the problem contains bounds;
00205 c       lsave(3) = .true.  each variable has upper and lower bounds.
00206 c
00207 c     isave is an INTEGER working array of dimension 44.
00208 c       On exit with task = 'NEW_X', it contains information that
00209 c       the user may want to access:
00210 c         isave(30) = the current iteration number;
00211 c         isave(34) = the total number of function and gradient
00212 c                         evaluations;
00213 c         isave(36) = the number of function value or gradient
00214 c                                  evaluations in the current iteration;
00215 c         isave(38) = the number of free variables in the current
00216 c                         iteration;
00217 c         isave(39) = the number of active constraints at the current
00218 c                         iteration;
00219 c
00220 c         see the subroutine setulb.f for a description of other 
00221 c         information contained in isave
00222 c
00223 c     dsave is a DOUBLE PRECISION working array of dimension 29.
00224 c       On exit with task = 'NEW_X', it contains information that
00225 c         the user may want to access:
00226 c         dsave(2) = the value of f at the previous iteration;
00227 c         dsave(5) = the machine precision epsmch generated by the code;
00228 c         dsave(13) = the infinity norm of the projected gradient;
00229 c
00230 c         see the subroutine setulb.f for a description of other 
00231 c         information contained in dsave
00232 c
00233 c     --------------------------------------------------------------
00234 c           END OF THE DESCRIPTION OF THE VARIABLES IN L-BFGS-B
00235 c     --------------------------------------------------------------
00236 c
00237 c     << An example of subroutine 'timer' for AIX Version 3.2 >>
00238 c
00239 c     subroutine timer(ttime)
00240 c     double precision ttime
00241 c     integer itemp, integer mclock
00242 c     itemp = mclock()
00243 c     ttime = dble(itemp)*1.0d-2
00244 c     return
00245 c     end
00246 c-----------------------------------------------------------------------
00247 */
